DEFINITION
term:         Disparate Impact
plain:        Disparate impact occurs when a seemingly neutral policy or model disproportionately harms a protected group, regardless of intent.
technical:    Measured via the four-fifths rule: if the selection rate for any protected group is less than 80% (4/5) of the rate for the group with the highest rate, disparate impact may be present.
domain:       Legal and algorithmic fairness
related:      demographic parity, disparate treatment, four-fifths rule, adverse impact
misconception: Disparate impact does not require proof of discriminatory intent — it is an outcome-based measure, unlike disparate treatment which requires intentional discrimination.
source_quote: "The touchstone is business necessity."
---
NOTES
Disparate impact originated in US employment law from Griggs v. Duke Power Co. (1971) and was codified in the Civil Rights Act of 1991. The four-fifths rule from the EEOC Uniform Guidelines provides a practical threshold. In machine learning, Feldman et al. (2015) formalised computational approaches to detecting and mitigating disparate impact in automated decision systems.
